Taxpayer was convicted in the United States District Court for the Eastern District of California of violations of statute declaring it a felony to willfully make and subscribe, under penalty of perjury, false income tax returns, and he appealed. The United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit, 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1972108395&pubNum=350&originatingDoc=Iab8979469bf011d991d0cc6b54f12d4d&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Search)" }{\fldrslt 
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf5 \i0 
455 F.2d 612,
}}}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb200 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
 reversed and remanded on ground that trial court erred in rejecting proffered instruction embodying offense under statute declaring it a misdemeanor to willfully deliver or disclose to the Internal Revenue Service a return or document known by taxpayer to be fraudulent or to be false as to any material matter, and certiorari was granted. The Supreme Court, Mr. Justice Blackmun, held that the word \u8216\'3fwillfully\u8217\'3f has the same meaning in both statutes, connoting a voluntary, intentional violation of a known legal duty and a bad purpose or evil motive; and that, accordingly, where the only issue in dispute centered on degree of willfulness, so that conviction of the misdemeanor would clearly support the conviction for the felony, lesser included offense instruction was not required or proper.
\par 
}
}
}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
